pros:
Get to meet some interesting people (i.e. people widely traveled, from obscure countries etc.);

Internationally focused environment - opportunities to travel abroad if you're at a more senior level;

Good pay (only at more senior levels);

IMC does some good work in the 'the field';

Slightly informal atmosphere (i.e. no one really cares if you show up 15 minutes late etc.)

cons:
Too many to count. Suffice to say that I started at IMC brimming with enthusiasm and hoping to kick-start a career in the charity sector, but upon leaving vowed never to work for an NGO/NFP ever again. Some examples:

Horrendous atmosphere in office. Bullying used as a management technique esp. for less senior, more 'generic' (i.e. expendable) roles. This is commented upon and seemingly accepted by other staff. Numerous tiresome office rivalries and conflicts - I naively thought that this would be less of an issue at an NGO - I was wrong;

Management have little to no interest in providing career progression opportunities for staff. As a result of this (and the above) staff turnover is very high (don't just take my word for it - check out some ex-employees on LinkedIn to see how long the average tenure is - 1-2 years is common). My manager for example interrupted my Annual Review to take a call from her husband about an upcoming holiday  - and then spent 10 minutes discussing it whilst I sat there like a lemon;

Everything is done in a very 'back of an envelope' way i.e. with little forethought, discussion or preparation. A few senior staff members make random decisions on a whim and everyone has to make it work. One employee I stayed in touch with told me that she felt that working at IMC was like working for a family business;

Obscene waste of funds and donations on fripperies such as pointless foreign trips, expensive hotels or useless IT equipment. This is one of the reasons I no longer give money to charity;

Huge pay differentials, often between staff doing the same job - there's a reason there's no payscale advertised on IMC's website. Pay for the less prestigious jobs is low and not enough to live on in London;

HQ is in LA, which is just about the most awkward location possible given that the vast bulk of IMC's programmes are in Asia and Africa. For urgent matters this means hanging around way past your leaving time waiting for people to arrive to work in LA;

London office location - who thought Canary Wharf, one of the dullest, most sterile parts of London - would be a good location for an NGO? Though I suppose it's an improvement on the old office which was a decaying hovel with no disabled access.

I could go on. I certainly learned a few things at IMC, though dealing with the above day-in-day-out for well below the London living wage started making me extremely jaded and cynical so I eventually just quit. I'd like to think that IMC has changed radically since I left though somehow I doubt it. I notice that a good third to a half of the staff members who were there when I was have since left. I'd recommend it maybe for a year or so if you are absolutely determined to work in the NGO field just to get some experience under your belt, and then move on to somewhere more professionally run.
